    chronologyEn: [
      'Susanoo rampages through Takamagahara, destroying sacred rice paddies and defiling Amaterasu\'s harvest hall.',
      'Susanoo hurls a flayed heavenly horse into the Sacred Weaving Hall, killing the weaver Wakahirume.',
      'Amaterasu, overcome with horror and rage, hides inside the Ama-no-Iwato cave and seals it with a boulder.',
      'The world falls into eternal darkness; the eight hundred myriad deities gather at the Ame-no-Yasu-no-Kawara river.',
      'Omoikane devises a plan; Ishikoridome forges the mirror Yata-no-Kagami and Tama-no-oya strings the magatama jewels.',
      'Ame-no-Uzume dances atop a wooden tub and bares her body, provoking a thunderous laughter among the gods.',
      'Curious, Amaterasu opens the cave door and is captivated by her own reflection in the mirror.',
      'Tajikarao pulls Amaterasu out; Futodama seals the cave with the shimenawa rope; light returns and Susanoo is banished.',
    ],
    impact: '''Kembalinya cahaya Amaterasu ke dunia menyelamatkan seluruh kosmos dari kehancuran abadi, menegaskan posisinya sebagai dewi tertinggi dan leluhur ilahi dari garis kekaisaran Jepang. Tiga pusaka yang digunakan untuk memancingnya keluar, yakni cermin Yata-no-Kagami, permata Yasakani-no-Magatama, dan kelak pedang Kusanagi dari kisah Susanoo, menjadi Tiga Pusaka Suci Kekaisaran (Sanshu no Jingi) yang mengesahkan kekuasaan setiap kaisar Jepang hingga era modern. Pengusiran Susanoo dari Takamagahara menjadi titik awal petualangannya di dunia manusia, membuka jalan bagi kisah besar berikutnya: pertarungannya melawan naga berkepala delapan, Yamata no Orochi, di tanah Izumo.''',
    impactEn: '''The return of Amaterasu's light saved the entire cosmos from eternal ruin, affirming her position as the supreme deity and divine ancestor of Japan's imperial line. The three treasures used to lure her out, the mirror Yata-no-Kagami, the jewel Yasakani-no-Magatama, and later the sword Kusanagi from Susanoo's own tale, became the Three Sacred Treasures of the Imperial Regalia (Sanshu no Jingi), which legitimize the authority of every Japanese emperor into the modern era. Susanoo's banishment from Takamagahara marked the beginning of his adventures in the mortal world, paving the way for the next great tale: his battle against the eight-headed serpent, Yamata no Orochi, in the land of Izumo.''',
    meaning: '''Kisah persembunyian Amaterasu menjadi mitos matahari (sun myth) paling penting dalam Shinto, menjelaskan siklus siang dan malam sekaligus menegaskan bahwa terang dan tatanan dunia bergantung pada kesucian dan keharmonisan hubungan antardewa. Kekacauan yang ditimbulkan Susanoo melambangkan kekuatan destruktif yang mengancam Ma'at versi Jepang, sementara musyawarah para dewa dan tarian Ame-no-Uzume menunjukkan bahwa tawa, kegembiraan, dan kerja sama komunitas mampu mengatasi bahkan krisis kosmis terbesar sekalipun. Cermin Yata-no-Kagami menjadi simbol kebenaran dan kejujuran dalam Shinto, dipercaya sebagai wadah bagi roh (mitama) Amaterasu sendiri, dan hingga kini disemayamkan di Kuil Ise, tempat suci paling agung dalam agama Shinto, sebagai penghubung langsung antara dunia manusia dan sang dewi matahari.''',
    meaningEn: '''The tale of Amaterasu's withdrawal stands as the most important sun myth in Shinto belief, explaining the cycle of day and night while affirming that light and the order of the world depend on the purity and harmony of relationships among the gods. The chaos wrought by Susanoo symbolizes the destructive forces that threaten the Japanese equivalent of cosmic order, while the deities' council and Ame-no-Uzume's dance show that laughter, joy, and communal cooperation can overcome even the greatest cosmic crisis. The mirror Yata-no-Kagami became a symbol of truth and honesty in Shinto belief, held to be the vessel of Amaterasu's own spirit (mitama), and to this day it is enshrined at Ise Grand Shrine, Shinto's most sacred site, serving as a direct link between the human world and the sun goddess herself.''',
  ),
  MythStory(
    id: 'japanese-susanoo-orochi',
    mythology: 'Japanese',
    icon: '🐉',
    imageUrl: 'assets/images/Japanese/History/susanoyamata.webp',
    title: 'Susanoo Membunuh Yamata no Orochi',
    titleEn: 'Susanoo Slays Yamata no Orochi',
    summary: 'Diusir dari surga, Susanoo tiba di Izumo dan menyelamatkan Kushinada-hime dari naga berkepala delapan Yamata no Orochi dengan memabukkannya lewat sake, lalu menemukan pedang Kusanagi di dalam ekor naga yang telah ia cincang.',
    summaryEn: 'Banished from heaven, Susanoo arrives in Izumo and saves Kushinada-hime from the eight-headed serpent Yamata no Orochi by getting it drunk on sake, then discovers the sword Kusanagi hidden within the serpent\'s tail after hewing it apart.',
    timeline: 'Zaman Para Dewa · Naga Berkepala Delapan',
    timelineEn: 'Age of the Gods · The Eight-Headed Serpent',
    chapters: [
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Pengasingan Susanoo ke Izumo',
        headingEn: 'Susanoo\'s Exile to Izumo',
        body: '''Setelah diusir dari Takamagahara sebagai hukuman atas kekacauan yang ia timbulkan hingga membuat Amaterasu bersembunyi di dalam gua, Susanoo turun ke bumi dan mendarat di provinsi Izumo, di hulu Sungai Hi (Hi-no-Kawa), dengan jubah janggut yang telah dicukur dan kuku yang telah dicabut sebagai tanda hukumannya. Ketika mengembara sendirian di tepi sungai, ia melihat sepasang sumpit makan hanyut mengalir dari hulu, sebuah pertanda bahwa ada orang yang tinggal lebih jauh ke arah pegunungan. Mengikuti aliran sungai ke atas, Susanoo menemukan sepasang dewa tua bumi, Ashinazuchi dan istrinya Tenazuchi, yang sedang menangis tersedu-sedu sambil memeluk seorang gadis muda. Susanoo, penasaran dan berniat menolong, mendekati mereka dan bertanya sebab kesedihan yang begitu mendalam itu. Meski Susanoo baru saja diusir dari surga karena kekerasannya, di Izumo ia mendapat kesempatan baru untuk menunjukkan sisi lain dari dirinya sebagai pelindung, bukan lagi sebagai perusak tatanan surgawi.''',
        bodyEn: '''After being banished from Takamagahara as punishment for the chaos he had caused, which drove Amaterasu into hiding within the cave, Susanoo descended to earth and landed in the province of Izumo, at the headwaters of the Hi River (Hi-no-Kawa), his beard shaved and his nails torn out as marks of his punishment. Wandering alone along the riverbank, he saw a pair of chopsticks drifting downstream from upriver, a sign that people must live somewhere further toward the mountains. Following the river upstream, Susanoo came upon an elderly pair of earthly deities, Ashinazuchi and his wife Tenazuchi, weeping bitterly while embracing a young girl. Susanoo, curious and moved to help, approached them and asked the cause of such deep sorrow. Though Susanoo had just been banished from heaven for his violence, in Izumo he found a new chance to show another side of himself, that of a protector, rather than a destroyer of heavenly order.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Kisah Naga Pemakan Manusia',
        headingEn: 'The Tale of the Man-Eating Serpent',
        body: '''Ashinazuchi menjelaskan bahwa mereka dahulu memiliki delapan putri, namun setiap tahun, seekor naga mengerikan bernama Yamata no Orochi datang dari pegunungan untuk melahap satu putri mereka. Orochi digambarkan sebagai makhluk raksasa dengan delapan kepala dan delapan ekor, matanya merah menyala seperti buah cherry musim dingin, tubuhnya begitu panjang hingga membentang melintasi delapan lembah dan delapan puncak gunung sekaligus, sementara perutnya senantiasa basah oleh darah dan daging korban-korbannya, ditumbuhi lumut, cemara, dan pohon cedar di sepanjang punggungnya. Kini tujuh dari delapan putri mereka telah tiada, dimakan satu demi satu setiap tahun, dan musim naga itu datang kembali sudah dekat, sementara satu-satunya putri yang tersisa, Kushinada-hime, "Putri Pematang Sawah Ajaib", akan menjadi mangsa berikutnya. Mendengar kisah tragis itu, Susanoo, tergerak oleh kecantikan dan keberanian Kushinada-hime yang pasrah menerima nasibnya, menawarkan diri untuk membunuh Orochi, dengan syarat Ashinazuchi dan Tenazuchi bersedia menikahkannya dengan Kushinada-hime seandainya ia berhasil.''',
        bodyEn: '''Ashinazuchi explained that they once had eight daughters, but every year, a terrible serpent named Yamata no Orochi came down from the mountains to devour one of their daughters. Orochi was described as a monstrous creature with eight heads and eight tails, its eyes glowing red like winter cherries, its body so immense that it stretched across eight valleys and eight mountain peaks at once, its belly forever wet with the blood and flesh of its victims, its back overgrown with moss, cypress, and cedar trees. Now seven of their eight daughters were gone, devoured one by one each year, and the serpent's season was drawing near again, with their sole remaining daughter, Kushinada-hime, "Wondrous Rice-Paddy Princess," destined to be its next victim. Hearing this tragic tale, Susanoo, moved by the beauty and quiet courage of Kushinada-hime, who accepted her fate with resignation, offered to slay Orochi, on the condition that Ashinazuchi and Tenazuchi agree to give him Kushinada-hime's hand in marriage should he succeed.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Persiapan Jebakan Sake Delapan Kali Suling',
        headingEn: 'Preparing the Trap of Eightfold Sake',
        body: '''Ashinazuchi dan Tenazuchi, meski ragu bahwa siapa pun dapat mengalahkan makhluk sebesar dan seganas Orochi, menerima tawaran Susanoo dengan penuh harap. Untuk melindungi Kushinada-hime selama pertempuran berlangsung, Susanoo menggunakan kekuatan sihirnya mengubah sang putri menjadi sebuah sisir bergigi rapat, yutsutsumagushi, yang kemudian ia selipkan dengan hati-hati ke dalam sanggul rambutnya sendiri, menjaganya tetap dekat dan aman dari bahaya. Ia lalu memerintahkan Ashinazuchi dan Tenazuchi untuk menyuling sake sebanyak delapan kali penyulingan berturut-turut, menghasilkan minuman yang disebut yashiozake, jauh lebih keras dan memabukkan daripada sake biasa. Susanoo juga memerintahkan agar dibangun sebuah pagar besar dengan delapan gerbang, disebut yaemagaki, dan di depan setiap gerbang didirikan sebuah panggung penyangga tempat diletakkannya satu bejana besar berisi sake pekat itu, sehingga total delapan bejana disiapkan, masing-masing tepat di hadapan salah satu dari delapan kepala Orochi yang diperkirakan akan datang menyerang dari arah pegunungan.''',
        bodyEn: '''Ashinazuchi and Tenazuchi, though doubtful that anyone could defeat a creature as vast and ferocious as Orochi, accepted Susanoo's offer with hopeful hearts. To protect Kushinada-hime during the coming battle, Susanoo used his magical power to transform the princess into a fine-toothed comb, the yutsutsumagushi, which he then carefully tucked into his own hair, keeping her close and safe from harm. He then ordered Ashinazuchi and Tenazuchi to distill sake through eight successive rounds of fermentation, producing a drink called yashiozake, far stronger and more intoxicating than ordinary sake. Susanoo also commanded the building of a great fence with eight gates, called the yaemagaki, and before each gate a raised platform was erected to hold one great vat filled with the potent sake, so that eight vats in total were prepared, each positioned directly before one of Orochi's eight heads, expected to descend from the mountains to attack.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Pertarungan dan Penemuan Pedang Kusanagi',
        headingEn: 'The Battle and the Discovery of the Kusanagi Sword',
        body: '''Ketika malam tiba, Yamata no Orochi muncul dari balik pegunungan, tubuhnya yang raksasa merayap turun dengan suara gemuruh mengerikan seperti guntur. Mencium aroma sake yang menggoda, kedelapan kepala naga itu masing-masing menjulurkan lehernya ke salah satu dari delapan bejana yang telah disiapkan, lalu meminum habis isinya dengan rakus. Yashiozake yang begitu keras segera bekerja, membuat kedelapan kepala Orochi menjadi mabuk berat hingga naga raksasa itu ambruk dan tertidur pulas tepat di tempatnya. Melihat kesempatan itu, Susanoo segera menghunus pedang panjangnya, Totsuka-no-Tsurugi, dan menyerang dengan ganas, mencincang tubuh Orochi kepala demi kepala, ekor demi ekor, hingga Sungai Hi yang mengalir di dekatnya berubah merah pekat oleh darah naga itu. Ketika Susanoo mencapai ekor keempat dari naga itu, pedangnya tiba-tiba terantuk sesuatu yang keras dan patah sedikit matanya. Penasaran, ia membelah ekor itu lebih dalam dan menemukan sebilah pedang agung tersembunyi di dalamnya, berkilau tajam luar biasa, yang kemudian dinamai Ame-no-Murakumo-no-Tsurugi, "Pedang Pengumpul Awan Surgawi".''',
        bodyEn: '''When night fell, Yamata no Orochi emerged from behind the mountains, its colossal body slithering down with a terrifying, thunderous roar. Drawn by the enticing scent of sake, each of the serpent's eight heads stretched its neck toward one of the eight prepared vats and drank the contents down greedily. The potent yashiozake took swift effect, leaving all eight of Orochi's heads thoroughly drunk until the massive serpent collapsed and fell into a deep sleep right where it lay. Seizing the moment, Susanoo drew his long sword, Totsuka-no-Tsurugi, and attacked with fury, hacking through Orochi's body head by head, tail by tail, until the nearby Hi River ran thick and red with the serpent's blood. When Susanoo reached the fourth tail of the beast, his blade suddenly struck something hard and chipped at its edge. Curious, he cut deeper into the tail and discovered a magnificent sword hidden within, gleaming with extraordinary sharpness, which he named Ame-no-Murakumo-no-Tsurugi, the "Sword of the Gathering Heavenly Clouds."''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Penutup: Kusanagi dan Pusaka Kekaisaran',
        headingEn: 'Closing: Kusanagi and the Imperial Regalia',
        body: '''Setelah membunuh Yamata no Orochi dan menyelamatkan Kushinada-hime, Susanoo mempersembahkan pedang agung yang ditemukannya itu kepada Amaterasu di surga, sebagai tanda perdamaian dan penebusan atas kekacauan yang pernah ia timbulkan di Takamagahara. Amaterasu menerima persembahan itu dengan lapang dada, dan pedang tersebut kelak menjadi terkenal dengan nama Kusanagi-no-Tsurugi, "Pedang Pemotong Rumput", setelah digunakan oleh pahlawan Yamato Takeru berabad-abad kemudian untuk memotong rerumputan dan menyelamatkan diri dari kobaran api yang dinyalakan musuh-musuhnya. Pedang ini kemudian menjadi salah satu dari Tiga Pusaka Suci Kekaisaran Jepang, bersama cermin Yata-no-Kagami dan permata Yasakani-no-Magatama, dan hingga kini disimpan di Kuil Atsuta di Nagoya sebagai simbol keabsahan takhta kekaisaran. Susanoo sendiri mengubah kembali sisir itu menjadi Kushinada-hime, menikahinya, dan membangun sebuah istana megah di Suga, tempat ia menggubah puisi waka pertama dalam sejarah Jepang, "Yakumo tatsu, Izumo yae-gaki...", menandai kelahirannya kembali sebagai pahlawan dan leluhur para penguasa Izumo.''',
        bodyEn: '''After slaying Yamata no Orochi and saving Kushinada-hime, Susanoo presented the magnificent sword he had found to Amaterasu in heaven, as a token of peace and atonement for the chaos he had once caused in Takamagahara. Amaterasu accepted the offering graciously, and the sword would later become famous under the name Kusanagi-no-Tsurugi, the "Grass-Cutting Sword," after it was used centuries later by the hero Yamato Takeru to cut down grass and save himself from a fire set by his enemies. This sword went on to become one of the Three Sacred Treasures of the Japanese Imperial Regalia, alongside the mirror Yata-no-Kagami and the jewel Yasakani-no-Magatama, and to this day it is enshrined at Atsuta Shrine in Nagoya as a symbol of the legitimacy of the imperial throne. Susanoo himself transformed the comb back into Kushinada-hime, married her, and built a magnificent palace at Suga, where he composed the first waka poem in Japanese history, "Yakumo tatsu, Izumo yae-gaki...", marking his rebirth as a hero and ancestor of the rulers of Izumo.''',
      ),
